photo.title: "Museums in Motion"

description._content: The nonprofit Market Street Railway that supports the operation of MUNI's historic trolleys in San Francisco calls the fleet a "museum in motion." But to simply categorize the city's streetcars as museum pieces is disingenuous. Every day, two dozen historic streetcars hit the streets of San Francisco to move upwards of 25,000 commuters and visitors. From dawn until well into the night, this fleet of PCCs built in the 1930s and 1940s move people through the heart of the city, just like they did in the years immediately after World War II when more than 4,500 of the streamlined streetcars ran in 33 cities across continent. These cars may look like museum pieces, but don't for a second think they're static.

photo.title: But wait

description._content: But Wait! The Critique: Extreme perspective creates drama and immediate impact. This is not my normal point of view and it intrigues me – invites me to look closer. Nice focus throughout the depth of the photograph. The off kilter frame enhances the unreality resulting from the low perspective angle. Good balance of elements and fun spatial relationships due to the wide angle lens. Nice overhead light illuminates all the details. The shot is whimsical – elicits a smile. What I had learned. I seemed to be pretty invisible sitting on the ground. Sometimes, like here, I wasn’t sure that was a good thing.
